RONALD CLARK SITS DOWN WITH HIS DAUGHTER JAMILAH TO TELL HER ABOUT HIS CHILDHOOD.
AT FIRST, HE IS SITTING AT THE DINNER TABLE WITH HIS PARENTS AND HE MENTIONS HOW THANKFUL HE IS THAT THEY ARE RICH.
HIS PARENTS LOOK AT HIM INCREDULOUSLY AND TELL HIM THAT THEY ARE NOT RICH BUT ARE IN FACT, POOR.
SOON HIS FATHER GETS A JOB AS A JANITOR AT THE LIBRARY.
DURING THIS TIME, MANY LIBRARIANS LIVED IN THE LIBRARIES IN WHICH THEY WORKED, SO ARNOLD'S FAMILY MOVED IN TO THE LIBRARY.
HE WAS EMBARRASSED TO TAKE HIS FRIENDS BACK "HOME" BECAUSE NONE OF HIS OTHER FRIENDS LIVED IN A LIBRARY, AND AS A KID, HE JUST WANTED TO BE NORMAL.
MANY OTHER LIBRARIES WERE NOT KEPT IN SUCH PRISTINE CONDITION AS HIS FATHER'S.
THEY HAD DUST AND GUM WRAPPERS LYING AROUND, BUT NOT HIS FATHER'S LIBRARY.
HIS FATHER TOOK GREAT PRIDE IN HIS DUTIES THERE AND EVERYTHING WAS SHINY AND WAXED.
HE EVEN DUSTED THE TOP OF THE BOOKSHELVES, SO WHEN YOU WOULD STAND ON THE STAIRS AND LOOK DOWN ON THEM, THERE WAS NO DUST.
THE NARRATOR REMEMBERS THAT HE HAD TO BE VERY QUIET IN THE LIBRARY DURING THE DAY, BUT THAT AT NIGHT ONCE IT CLOSED, HE HAD FREE REIGN AND COULD RUN AND SCREAM AND JUMP AND PLAY.
AT NIGHT, IF HE COULDN'T SLEEP, OR HAD A QUESTION ABOUT SOMETHING, HE WOULD JUST GO DOWNSTAIRS AND LOOK IT UP IN A BOOK.
HE LEARNED MANY THINGS FROM THE BOOKS IN HIS FATHER'S LIBRARY.
HE BECAME THE FIRST PERSON IN HIS ENTIRE FAMILY THROUGHOUT THE GENERATIONS TO GO TO COLLEGE.
IN FACT, HE BECAME A PROFESSOR.
ONE DAY HE BROUGHT HIS FATHER TO SEE HIS CLASSROOM AND HE SAW THE "PROFESSOR" NAMEPLATE ON THE DOOR.
HIS FATHER WAS THE SILENT TYPE, BUT HE SAW THE LOOK ON HIS FATHER'S FACE AND KNEW HOW PROUD HE WAS.
HE SAID THAT WITHOUT BEING EXPOSED TO SO MANY BOOKS GROWING UP, HIS LIFE WOULD NOT BE AS RICH AND FULFILLING AS IT IS TODAY.
AS THE ANIMATED PORTION OF THE STORY ENDED, WE SEE A PICTURE OF THE REAL FATHER AND DAUGHTER WHO HAD BEEN NARRATING THE STORY.
THE STORY IS AN ANIMATED FILM NARRATED BY AND ELDERLY GENTLEMAN ABOUT HIS YOUTH.
HE SPEAKS ABOUT GROWING UP IN THE 1940S.
AT FIRST HE LIVES IN A SMALL APARTMENT/HOME WITH HIS MOTHER AND FATHER.
HE TELLS THEM THAT HE IS VERY GLAD THAT THEY ARE RICH.
THEY TELL HIM THAT THEY ARE NOT RICH, BUT IN FACT, ARE POOR.
THEN HIS FATHER GETS A JOB IN THE LIBRARY AS A JANITOR.
IN THIS ERA, LIBRARY WORKERS OFTEN LIVED IN THE LIBRARIES IN WHICH THEY WORKED, SO THE YOUNG BOY AND HIS FAMILY MOVE INTO THE LIBRARY.
HE BOASTS ABOUT HIS FATHER'S LIBRARY BEING THE CLEANEST LIBRARY AROUND, WITHOUT TRASH DEBRIS, GUM WRAPPERS, OR DUST.
HIS FATHER ALWAYS KEPT EVERYTHING METICULOUSLY CLEANED, DUSTED, AND WAXED.
HE EVEN WAXED THE TOP OF THE BOOKSHELVES!
THE YOUNG BOY HAD TO BE QUIET DURING THE DAY TIME, SINCE IT WAS A LIBRARY, BUT DURING THE NIGHT AFTER CLOSING TIME, HE WAS THE ONLY KID IN THE ENTIRE BUILDING.
HE COULD RUN, SCREAM, JUMP, PLAY, AND BE AS LOUD AS HE WANTED.
AT BED TIME HE WOULD OFTEN STAY UP READING UNTIL 3AM!
IF HE EVER HAD ANY QUESTIONS ABOUT ANYTHING, HE COULD SIMPLY GO DOWNSTAIRS AND PICK UP A BOOK AND FIND THE ANSWER.
THIS HELPED HIM BECOME THE FIRST PERSON IN HIS FAMILY TO GO TO AND GRADUATE FROM COLLEGE.
IN FACT, HE EVENTUALLY BECAME A PROFESSOR.
WHEN HE BROUGHT HIS FATHER TO HIS CLASSROOM ONE DAY, HE SHOWED HIS FATHER HIS NAMEPLATE ON THE DOOR THAT READ "PROFESSOR".
HIS FATHER WAS A VERY QUIET MAN, BUT HE COULD SEE ON HIS FATHER'S FACE (THE LOOK IN HIS EYES) THAT HE WAS PROUD OF HIS SON FOR ACHIEVING A LIFE BETTER THAN HE HAD.
THE MAN SAYS THAT WITHOUT BEING EXPOSED TO BOOKS IN THE LIBRARY THROUGHOUT HIS LIFE, HE WOULD NOT HAVE BEEN ABLE TO EXCEL AS HE DID.
THE FILM ENDS WITH A REAL LIFE PHOTO OF HIM AND HIS DAUGHTER, JAMILAH.
